message.content:
To align a row of `div` elements to the right using Flexbox in CSS, you can use the `flex-direction` property and set it to `row-reverse`. This will reverse the direction of the flex container, effectively aligning the elements to the left (since we started from the default right alignment).

Alternatively, you can also use `justify-content: flex-start;` on the child elements (`div`) to achieve the same result.

Here's an example:

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-end; /* or justify-content: flex-start; */
}

.item {
  width: 100px;
  height: 50px;
  margin: 10px;
  background-color: #f2f2f2;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
}

/* example usage */
<div class="container">
  <div class="item">Item 1</div>
  <div class="item">Item 2</div>
  <div class="item">Item 3</div>
  <div class="item">Item 4</div>
</div>
```

In this example, the `.container` element has `display: flex` set to display its child elements as a flexible container. The `justify-content: flex-end;` property is used on the `.container` element to align its child elements (`.item`) to the right.

If you want to use `flex-direction: row-reverse;`, it would look like this:

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row-reverse;
}

.item {
  width: 100px;
  height: 50px;
  margin: 10px;
  background-color: #f2f2f2;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
}
```

Both approaches will achieve the same result, but using `justify-content` on the child elements can be more flexible and easier to manage in some cases.
